This function acts as a factory for coloring, generating specialized functions tailored to your desired hue. It first detects whether the execution environment supports full 256-color mode or must fall back to simpler schemes using ANSI escape sequences.

```python
def color(number):
    """
    Returns a function that colors a string with a number from 0 to 255.
    """
    if supports_256():
        template = "\033[38;5;{number}m{text}\033[0m"
    else:
        template = "\033[{number}m{text}\033[0m"
    def _color(text):
        if not all([sys.stdout.isatty(), sys.stderr.isatty()]):
            return text
        else:
            return template.format(number=number, text=text)
    return _color
```

The inner `_color` function provides robustness by checking if output is sent directly to an interactive terminal (`sys.stdout.isatty()`). This prevents color codes from leaking into files or non-interactive logs.
